=======================================
Method Reference is a shorthand syntax in Java used to refer to:
    - a method
    - or a constructor
without actually calling them right now.

They are used wherever a functional interface is expected.

üëâ Think of a method reference as giving a method‚Äôs address to Java
so Java can call it later when needed.


üéØ Why do we use Method References?
====================================
Because they make the code:
    - shorter
    - cleaner
    - readable
    - more expressive

Compare:
Lambda:             >>>>>>>>> list.forEach(x -> System.out.println(x));
Method Reference:   >>>>>>>>> list.forEach(System.out::println);


